  Weber's and Habermas's developmental accounts.

  POSITION: Critical comparative reading -- situates Habermas as one of three
  post-Weberian responses to modernity, each inheriting Weber's problematic
  while attempting to overcome it.
  },
  keywords = {Weber, Habermas, Arendt, MacIntyre, modernity, rationalization, developmental-history, High, INCOMPLETE, no-abstract}
}

@article{conill2025nueva,
  author = {Conill-Sancho, Jes{\'u}s},
  title = {Nueva filosof{\'i}a geneal{\'o}gica y sociol{\'o}gica de la religi{\'o}n},
  journal = {Revista Portuguesa de Filosofia},
  year = {2025},
  volume = {81},
  number = {3},
  pages = {805--826},
  doi = {10.17990/rpf/2025_81_3_0805},
  abstract = {The purpose of this contribution is to support a new task of philosophy of religion: its transformation through genealogy as philosophical and sociological method. Starting point of this new approach is found according to several authors from Jaspers in the so-called axial age. Taking the discourse on faith and knowledge as a guiding thread Habermas carries out a genealogy or history of thought that examines how the religious can be found even in the background of some forms of contemporary postmetaphysical philosophy. In his work, especially in his latest book Auch eine Geschichte der Philosophie Habermas develops a genealogy of thought from its religious roots, but accepts the Weberian thesis of secularization. However Joas proposes an alternative to the Weberian and Habermasian conception of secularizing rationalization, because Joas considers that such a conception is problematic.},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Conill-Sancho examines the genealogical method in Habermas's
  most recent work (Also a History of Philosophy, 2023), arguing that Habermas
  accepts the Weberian secularization thesis while subjecting it to genealogical
  reconstruction. Hans Joas's alternative to both Weber and Habermas on
  secularizing rationalization is presented as a corrective, suggesting the
  Weberian framework is more limiting for Habermas than often acknowledged.

  RELEVANCE: Addresses the most recent phase of the Habermas-Weber relationship
  in philosophy of history, specifically how Habermas's 2023 genealogy of
  postmetaphysical thinking relates to Weber's secularization thesis. Brings
  the Habermas-Weber-Joas triangle into view for the question of historical
  development and religion.

  POSITION: Locates Habermas as accepting key elements of Weber's historical
  thesis while Joas represents a more thoroughgoing alternative.
  },
  keywords = {Habermas, Weber, secularization, genealogy, axial-age, philosophy-of-history, postmetaphysical, Medium}
}
